1. Project Introduction

Prieska Power Reserve (PPR) is a catalytic green hydrogen and ammonia production facility located in Prieska, Northern Cape, South Africa. The project leverages the region's exceptional solar irradiance and consistent wind resources to produce green hydrogen via electrolysis, with downstream conversion to green ammonia.

A key element of the project's feasibility assessment is the comprehensive measurement of on-site climate conditions. In July 2022, a 140-metre guyed lattice wind measurement mast (MKT-450) was installed at the project site to collect high-resolution meteorological data including wind speed, wind direction, temperature, barometric pressure, and humidity.

This report presents the analysis of three full years of climate data (2023, 2024, and 2025) recorded at 15-minute intervals by the mast's instrumentation suite. The data confirms the site's exceptional wind resource â€” particularly the strong, consistent night-time wind pattern that complements daytime solar generation, making Prieska an ideal location for 24/7 green hydrogen production.

Data Source

All data in this report is sourced from the Ammonit Meteo-40L data logger (serial D221018) installed on the MKT-450 mast at coordinates 29Â°48'11.98"S, 22Â°45'46.63"E, at a base elevation of 1,318m above sea level. Data is recorded in UTCÂ±00:00 at 15-minute intervals, yielding 105,216 records across the three-year period.

2. Wind Measurement Mast

The wind measurement campaign utilises a MKT-450 140m guyed lattice mast manufactured and installed by Windhunter Africa. The mast was commissioned on 5 August 2022 and has been operational continuously since, providing an uninterrupted high-quality meteorological dataset.

Key Observation: Wind direction at the Prieska site shows a consistent pattern across all three years: prevailing winds from the north-northeast (NNE) and north (N) sectors, particularly during the summer months (Octoberâ€“March). Winter months show more variable conditions with increased frequency from northwesterly directions. This pattern is characteristic of the Northern Cape semi-arid climate zone and is consistent with the regional wind resource assessment.

4. Wind Speed Analysis

Wind speed is measured by seven Thies First Class Advanced II anemometers distributed across the mast from 50m to 140m. Wind speed is averaged across all seven anemometers (50m to 140m) to provide a representative site-wide measurement. The primary anemometers at hub height (Anemometers 1â€“3 at 140m/135.6m) consistently register the highest speeds due to the vertical wind profile.

5. Temperature Analysis

Temperature is measured by a Galltec KPC.1.S/6-ME hygro-thermometer at 133.9m on the mast. The Prieska site experiences a semi-arid continental climate with hot summers and cool winters, typical of the Northern Cape interior at ~1,300m elevation.

6. Barometric Pressure Analysis

Barometric pressure is measured by an Ammonit S3310A barometer at 10m. At the site elevation of 1,318m, mean pressure is approximately 871 hPa. Pressure data has been filtered to exclude sensor anomalies (readings below 800 hPa). Seasonal variation reflects the typical Southern Hemisphere synoptic pattern with higher pressures in winter.

7. Humidity Analysis

Relative humidity is measured by the Galltec hygro-thermometer at 133.9m. The Prieska site is characteristically arid with an annual average humidity of approximately 39%. Summer months see occasional spikes due to convective rainfall events, while winter months are consistently dry.

Charts below show weekly resolution min/max/avg for each year.

8. Temperature & Wind Speed Overlay

Overlaying temperature and wind speed reveals the inverse seasonal relationship at Prieska: wind speeds tend to be highest during the cooler months (winter/spring) and moderate during the hotter summer months. This inverse correlation provides a natural balancing effect for energy production planning.

Key Findings

The three-year dataset demonstrates highly consistent wind conditions across all measurement years, with annual average wind speeds at hub height (140m) ranging from 7.24 to 7.66 m/s. Night-time wind speeds are consistently 1.5â€“2.5 m/s above daytime averages, confirming the site's suitability for complementary solar-wind energy generation. Temperature and pressure patterns show strong year-to-year repeatability, providing high confidence in the long-term resource assessment.
